fields.label_text: In the series Seven Years, Dublin-born Trish Morrissey investigates the iconography of family photographs and interrogates the relationships that underpin them. The series title refers to the age gap between Morrissey and her elder sister, with whom she collaborates. Together, they create elaborately staged images of themselves impersonating relatives, both real and imagined. Although the images suggest familiar memories re-enacted, the people rarely smile, which creates an atmosphere that is both nostalgic and unsettling.

Label for 'Making It Up: Photographic Fictions' (3 May 2013 - 12 January 2014):

Trish Morrissey (born 1967)
Untitled, 2001 
From the series Seven Years
2001

In her series Seven Years, Morrissey investigates family photographs and the relationships that lie behind them. The title refers to the age gap between Morrissey and her elder sister, with whom she collaborates. Together, they create elaborately staged images of themselves impersonating relatives, both real and imagined. The photographs imitate family snapshots, which are also often self-consciously posed. 


C-type print
Purchased through the Cecil Beaton Fund
Museum no. E.363-2005
